---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import BookBanner from '../../components/BookBanner.astro';
import { getServerSupabase } from '../../lib/supabase';

export const prerender = false;

// v32 — count published reviews so the footer link can carry the live N.
// RLS allows public reads of published reviews; we resolve the work id by
// slug then count. Failures degrade silently to a count of 0.
let reviewCount = 0;
try {
  const supabase = getServerSupabase(Astro);
  const { data: work } = await supabase
    .from('works')
    .select('id')
    .eq('slug', 'schools-of-the-republic')
    .maybeSingle();
  if (work?.id) {
    const { count } = await supabase
      .from('reviews')
      .select('id', { count: 'exact', head: true })
      .eq('work_id', work.id)
      .eq('is_published', true);
    if (typeof count === 'number') reviewCount = count;
  }
} catch {
  // swallow — the reviews link still renders with count 0.
}
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Schools of the Republic · America's School Trust Library"
  description="How the United States Built — and Largely Lost — a National Endowment for Public Education. The synthesizing analytic treatment of America's longest-running fiduciary experiment — the school-land trusts established at statehood, drawing on the per-state evidentiary record housed in the Library."
>
  <article class="prose">
    <span class="eyebrow">Volume I · Bird and Sullivan · 2025</span>
    <BookBanner direction="back" />
    <h1>Schools of the Republic</h1>
    <p class="kicker"><em>How the United States Built — and Largely Lost — a National Endowment for Public Education.</em> Volume 1 of a two-volume work, by Margaret Bird and Dave Sullivan, 2025. Substrate v1.3. Six era chapters of synthesis drawing on the Library's per-state record.</p>

    <p>
      <em>Schools of the Republic</em> is Volume 1 of the Looking Back /
      Looking Forward two-volume work — the synthesizing analytic treatment of
      America's longest-running fiduciary experiment — the school-land trusts created
      beginning with the 1785 Land Ordinance and extended through every state
      admission from Ohio to Hawaii. The book traces how the trusts were
      designed, how they have drifted, and what design principles their
      successor structures will need.
    </p>

    <p>
      The per-state evidentiary record this synthesis draws on lives in
      America's School Trust Library — in its
      <a href="/atlas/">Atlas</a>, its <a href="/maps/">Map Room</a>, and
      its <a href="/counting/">Counting House</a>, where it remains alive and
      continues to be added to. The book draws on that record without
      duplicating it.
    </p>

    <h2>The throughline — Prologue, six era chapters, conclusion</h2>
    <p>Six era chapters tracing the school-trust compact from the 1785 Land Ordinance through admission-era doublings, the school clause, fiduciary breach, and the constituency that remedies it.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/reading/prologue/">Prologue: Before the Section Lines</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/founding-floor/">Chapter 1: The Founding Floor</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/statehood-without-federal-floor/">Chapter 2: Statehood Without the Federal Floor</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/northwest-ordinance-template/">Chapter 3: The Northwest Ordinance Template</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/antebellum-doubling/">Chapter 4: The Antebellum Doubling</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/reconstruction-western-stack/">Chapter 5: Reconstruction and the Western Stack</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/twentieth-century-high-water-mark/">Chapter 6: The Twentieth-Century High-Water Mark and Two Outliers</a></li>
      <li><a href="/reading/conclusion/">Conclusion — Architecture, Constituency, and the Recovery That Is Possible</a></li>
    </ul>
    <p>For Volume I — and for the chapters above — the per-state evidentiary record lives in the Library's Atlas Room at schooltrusts.net.</p>

    <h2>The per-state record lives in the Library</h2>
    <p>
      The per-state dossiers — constitutional architecture, admission-act
      provisions, permanent fund corpus, federal grant acreage, and current
      trust-integrity status — live in the Library's
      <a href="/atlas/">Atlas</a>, with state cohort pages organized by era
      under <a href="/atlas/">/atlas/</a>. The same record surfaces in the
      <a href="/maps/">Map Room</a> for transparency posture and the
      <a href="/counting/">Counting House</a> for fund balances and audit
      disclosure.
    </p>

    <hr class="archival-divider">

    <p>This volume is the synthesis. The <a href="/atlas/">Atlas</a>, the <a href="/counting/">Counting House</a>, and the companion volume <a href="/reading/sacred-compact/">The Eighth Anchor</a> draw on the same evidentiary substrate.</p>

    <p class="reviews-link">
      <a href="/reading/schools-of-the-republic/reviews/">Reviews ({reviewCount})</a>
    </p>
  </article>

  <style>
    .reviews-link {
      font-family: var(--font-sans);
      font-size: 0.88rem;
      margin-top: 1.5rem;
      color: #475569;
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
